        <p align='center'>EQ GATHERING 3, THE DAY</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td width='100%' class='db' colspan='3'>The third EverQuest players
        gathering was held on July 9 at the Alexis Park Resort in Las Vegas,
        Nevada.&nbsp; The player gatherings are designed to provide an
        opportunity for players to meet each other away from the computer and
        generally have a good time.&nbsp; Whilst they are organised completely
        separate from Verant Interactive, the development team have made an
        effort since the first 'picnic in the park' to attend the events and
        meet some of their player-base.&nbsp; It is not a day designed to hammer
        away at Verant with questions about the game so much as an opportunity
        to learn a bit more about why the game is the way it is, and who the
        people are that have been behind it since its very inception.
        <p>The day began a little after 9 am on Sunday morning.&nbsp; There were
        a few late arrivals, myself included, as a result of the <a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/editorials/eqg3-1.asp'><b>night</b></a>
        before.&nbsp; But by 10am over 300 people had shuffled through the doors
        and were meeting and greeting each other.&nbsp; The day was kicked off
        with a speech by Brad McQuaid who introduced most of the staff from
        Verant who had arrived by this time.&nbsp; He then went on to surprise
        everyone with the unveiling of a new expansion, the Scars of Velious, to
        hopefully be released around December of this year.&nbsp; He explained
        that the expansion is going to be:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Designed for levels 35 - 60</li>
          <li>Most probably not include new player races, skills, or spells</li>
          <li>Will not increase the Level cap beyond 60</li>
          <li>Include a large number of new zones and monsters</li>
          <li>Include a new set of player models and textures with more polygons
          </li>
          <li>Include a new set of models and textures for armor, items and
            weapons</li>
          <li>Be based in an ice environment on the new continent of Velious</li>
          <li>Be sold as a retail product only</li>
        </ul>
        <p>After this there was brief discussion on the new toys EverQuest toys
        being designed by ToyVault.&nbsp; We first highlighted these to people
        back in May when they were debuted at the <a href='http://eq.castersrealm.com/editorials/e3-2000/'><b>E3
        Expo</b></a><b>.&nbsp; </b>The figurines have come a long way since then
        and now have armor and equipment accessories made for a lot of the
        player character toys, and some cool weapons for the monster toys.&nbsp;
        They should be going to retail stores in the very near future, as well
        as available for sale online.</p>
        <p>After the speeches were over players merged onto their table groups
        or lined up to receive their posters ort-shirts from the EQG3
        organisers.&nbsp; Unfortunately the Casters Realm T-shirts were
        impounded by US customs while I was bringing them over from Australia
        and I didn't get them until the day after the convention, so expect to
        see them coming online for purchase on the website soon.&nbsp; The
        Everlore team and the RPG Wear company had no problem with their shirts
        though, and they proved to be a popular item on the day.</p>
        <p>Time flew by as players related stories with each other from their
        servers, and it was particularly impressive to see some guilds have
        almost a complete turnout.&nbsp; The Grey guild from Xegony had a
        particularly large presence, and even had their own guild shirts.&nbsp;
        After lunch, the day then shifted into Event mode.&nbsp; The first event
        was a real life quest.&nbsp; Groups were formed based on servers and
        each group given a list of &quot;items&quot; from the EverQuest game
        which had to be somehow found in real life.&nbsp; Items included Orc
        Raider caps, Large Ruby's, Mammoth Tusks and more.&nbsp; It wasn't easy
        and the bug population was certainly diminished in Las Vegas as people
        swarmed around looking for a suitable scarab carapace, but overall it
        was a lot of fun.&nbsp; There were some very wild, or in truth
        desperate, attempts by people in finding certain objects, but thankfully
        no kill stealing or ninja looting of camps took place.&nbsp; There was
        certainly no shortage of guides around if needed to answer a petition
        though. </p>
        <p>The Quest finished around 3pm, and it was then time for the Trivia
        contest which was organised according to classes.&nbsp; This involved
        some difficult questions, especially for those just recovering from
        hangovers, on areas of the game which should have been fairly common
        knowledge to people.&nbsp; Surprisingly it all seemed so much harder
        back then.&nbsp; The first question asked for a listing of all the EQ
        Gods, this was followed by a question which asked for a number of
        different combinations of race and class to give the highest base of
        each stat, and then the lowest base of each stat.&nbsp; The next
        question asked for the first level spells of every caster class.&nbsp;
        Then we were asked to list every zone in the game.&nbsp; Lastly people
        were asked to list as many one handed slashing weapons and shields as
        possible.</p>
        <p>Before dinner a large number of Kunark posters were given out, and
        players quickly sought out Verant staff to get their copies
        signed.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dinner was a caesar salad and a chicken and rice meal if I remember
        correctly, but most people were simply nibbling away while talking shop
        and getting Verant staff members to sign posters or shirts.&nbsp; After
        dinner the prizes for the day were awarded for the days
        activities.&nbsp; Povar won the Quest event, and the Rangers won the
        Trivia event.&nbsp; Prizes included signed copies of the Ruins of
        Kunark.</p>
        <p>After that it was all over quite quickly, and players began saying
        their farewells and headed back out to the glitz and glamour of
        Vegas.&nbsp; It was a very fun day overall, and a big kudos to those who
        organised it.</p>
        <p>We do have some video footage of the event and hope to have it ready
        for viewing soon.</p>
        <p><i><font size='1'>Editorial by: Baelish Heartsbane</font></i></td>
